message.content:
The only non-terminal in the grammar that can produce the terminal ‘t70’ is NT82:

 NT82 → ‘t70’

NT82 appears on the right-hand side of exactly three binary rules:

 NT61 → NT82 NT34     (t70 would be the first symbol in the NT61 span)  
 NT2  → NT82 NT59     (t70 would be the first symbol in the NT2 span)  
 NT5  → NT41 NT82     (t70 would be the last symbol in the NT5 span)

Because the string ends with ‘t70’, the only possible way to place ‘t70’ in that position is through the rule

 NT5 → NT41 NT82

so the final two tokens of the string would have to be produced by NT5, with NT41 generating the penultimate token.

The penultimate token in the string is ‘t9’.  
Looking through all productions for NT41 we find that NT41 can yield

• the terminals t135, t4, t50, or t121, or  
• a string beginning with t79 or t112 (via NT58 …), or  
• a string beginning with t119, t31, t26, t130, t103, t82, t10, t99, t58, or t66 (via its other non-terminal productions).

NT41 cannot produce the terminal ‘t9’.  
Consequently NT5 cannot derive the substring “t9 t70”, and therefore no derivation in the grammar can place ‘t70’ at the end of the whole string.

Since every derivation of ‘t70’ would either put it at the start of a substring or require “t9 t70” at the end—both impossible—the given 21-token string cannot be generated by this grammar.

Answer: No

The only start-symbol rules are  

S → NT61 NT57  
S → NT37 NT47  
S → NT84 NT7  

The first word of the string is  t114.  
Among all single–terminal productions, the only non-terminal that can generate t114 is  

NT37 → 't114'

Therefore the only possible way to begin a derivation is

S ⇒ NT37 NT47

NT37 is always a single terminal, so it must cover just the first word t114.  
Consequently NT47 has to generate the remaining 20 words

t78 t99 t26 t89 t50 t47 t9 t66 t66 t22 t96 t105 t66 t66 t69 t72 t48 t68 t89 t50

NT47 has five rules:

NT47 → NT35 NT16  
NT47 → NT65 NT1  
NT47 → 't94' | 't43' | 't138'

Because the tail of the string has 20 words, NT47 cannot use one of its
one-terminal rules.  
For NT47 → NT65 NT1 to work, the final word would have to be the single-terminal
expansion of NT1, namely t48, but the last word of the string is t50, so this
alternative is impossible.

Thus the only remaining possibility is

NT47 ⇒ NT35 NT16

NT16 is defined only by

NT16 → NT48 NT21

and NT21 is a one-terminal non-terminal with

NT21 → 't9' | 't48' | 't50'

Hence the last word produced by NT16 must be t9, t48 or t50.  
Because the overall last word is t50, NT21 must supply that final t50, leaving NT48 to generate the preceding word sequence … t89 (the 20th word).

But NT48 can be a single terminal only if that terminal is t117, t89 or t83;
so the only way to match the “… t89 t50” tail is  

NT48 → 't89', NT21 → 't50'.

With that fixed, all the preceding 18 words, namely

t78 t99 t26 t89 t50 t47 t9 t66 t66 t22 t96 t105 t66 t66 t69 t72 t48 t68

must be generated by NT35.

NT35 has just

NT35 → 't78' | 't97' | 't109' | NT35 NT17 ,

so the very first word it produces has to be one of t78, t97, t109.
Indeed the first of those 18 words is t78, so we must use the rule

NT35 ⇒ 't78' NT17 NT17 … NT17            (one or more NT17’s)

and the remaining 17 words must be the concatenation of one or more
strings produced by NT17.

However every rule for NT17 introduces at least one of the terminals

t7 , t4 , t13 , t125 , t102 , t78 , t140 , t16 , t5

either directly (as a single-terminal rule) or as the final word of the
composite rule NT7 NT83 or NT16 NT46.

None of those symbols appears anywhere in the 17-word subsequence
t99 t26 t89 t50 t47 t9 t66 t66 t22 t96 t105 t66 t66 t69 t72 t48 t68.

Therefore no NT17 can generate any suffix of that subsequence, and a fortiori
no sequence of NT17’s can cover the whole 17-word block.

Hence the requirement that NT35 generate the 18-word section fails,
which in turn makes it impossible for NT47 to cover the last 20 words;
there is consequently no derivation starting with S ⇒ NT37 NT47.

Since the other two start rules are ruled out by the very first word,
the given string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

To obtain the given string the start symbol S must use one of its three productions

1. S → NT61 NT57  (last symbol would have to be t117, t49 or t37)  
2. S → NT37 NT47  (first symbol would have to be t50, t106, t114 or t21)  
3. S → NT84 NT7

The string starts with t45 and ends with t9, so only the third alternative can even be considered.

NT84 can either be a single terminal (t101 or t36) or the pair NT14 NT45.
NT14 only produces t45 and NT45 may produce t41, therefore  
NT84 ⇒ NT14 NT45 ⇒ t45 t41, matching exactly the first two symbols of the string.
Thus the remaining 28 symbols must be generated by NT7.

The only non-lexical rule for NT7 is

 NT7 → NT40 NT72  (lexical alternatives t125 and t102 are impossible because 28 symbols remain)

Hence the 28-symbol remainder has to split into a prefix generated by NT40 and a suffix generated by NT72.

• The first symbol of that remainder is t69.  
  NT40 can begin with t69 only through the production chain

 NT40 → NT60 NT58, NT60 → NT28 NT4, NT28 → t69

  In this chain the next symbols are supplied, in order, by NT4 (= NT30 NT71) and then by NT58.
  Consequently the beginning of every string produced by NT40 under this alternative has the form

 t69 t58/66 t22/69 t79/112,

  i.e. t69 followed by exactly one t58 or t66, then t22 or another t69, and finally t79 or t112.

  The actual string, however, starts with

 t69 t58 t58 t22 …

  (two consecutive t58’s before the t22), a pattern that NT40 can never deliver.

• The only other non-lexical alternative for NT40 is NT51 NT74.  
  Whatever NT51 produces, its very last symbol must be t92 (because the only way to keep NT51 in
  derivation and reach a t92 is NT51 → NT17 NT6 and NT6 → t92).  
  In the given string the first occurrence of t92 is the seventh symbol, yet the sixth symbol is t22.
  But NT51’s part (ending in t92) must be preceded by what NT17 can generate; examination of the
  possibilities for NT17 shows that none of them can end with t22.  Therefore the split
  NT40 → NT51 NT74 cannot match the prefix t69 t58 t58 t22 t92 either.

Because neither possibility for NT40 can match the required prefix, NT7 cannot generate the
28-symbol remainder, and thus S cannot generate the whole string.

Hence the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The first symbol of every sentence generated by the grammar must be produced by the left-most non-terminal in one of the three start rules

1. S → NT61 NT57
2. S → NT37 NT47
3. S → NT84 NT7

Only one non-terminal in the entire grammar can generate the terminal t106, namely NT37 (NT37 → 't106').  
Therefore the only possible expansion for S that could match the given string is

S → NT37 NT47

which would produce

t106                           rest-of-string
─── NT37 ───     ┌─────────────────────── NT47 ───────────────────────┐

Thus NT47 would have to generate the remaining 34 terminals

t109 t49 t70 t72 t125 t86 t71 t129 t108 t127 t66 t69 t112 t65 t101 t76 t71 t39
t66 t66 t69 t17 t108 t92 t87 t58 t89 t76 t47 t26 t24 t28 t9 t50

The non-terminal NT47 can expand only in the following ways:

NT47 → NT35 NT16  
NT47 → NT65 NT1  
NT47 → 't94' | 't43' | 't138'

The lexical alternatives ('t94', 't43', 't138') are single tokens, so they cannot cover 34 tokens.  
For the binary alternatives we look at the first token they can produce:

• NT35 can start with the lexical tokens t78, t97 or t109.  
• NT65 can start only with the lexical token t105 (or, via NT65 → NT39 NT35, with t10 or t99).  
• NT1 generates only the single token t48.  
• NT16 never produces a lexical token t49; its possible leading tokens are t117, t89, t83, t130, t103, t82, t65, … (through NT48 or NT68).

Consequently:

– If NT47 → NT35 NT16, the first token of NT47 must be t78, t97 or t109.  
  Given the string, it would have to be t109. After NT35 has produced this t109, the next
  token to be generated would have to be the first token produced by NT16. NT16 can never
  begin with t49, so this choice fails.

– If NT47 → NT65 NT1, the first token of NT47 would have to be t105, t10 or t99,
  none of which matches the required t109. This alternative also fails.

Since every possible expansion of NT47 is incompatible with the required remainder of the string, no derivation exists for the string starting from S.

Therefore the grammar does not generate the given string.

No

The first symbol of any sentence generated by the grammar must be produced by the left-hand member of one of the three start-rules  

S → NT84 NT7 | NT37 NT47 | NT61 NT57  

Since the given string begins with  t36  and the only lexical rule that yields  t36  is NT84 → 't36', the only viable start-rule is  

S → NT84 NT7,  
with NT84 generating the first token and NT7 having to generate the remaining 35 tokens.

NT7 can either be lexical (NT7 → 't125' / 't102') – impossible because 35 tokens remain – or must use its sole binary rule  

NT7 → NT40 NT72

Thus token 2 must be the first token produced by NT40.  
The only ways NT40 can start are

1. NT40 → 't3'   (first token is exactly t3)  
2. NT40 → NT60 NT58   (first token comes from NT28 → 't69' / 't127' / 't105')  
3. NT40 → NT51 NT74  (first token comes from NT51, whose lexical starter is t71 or t7)

The second token of the string is t3, so the only workable choice is NT40 → 't3'.  
Hence NT40 covers just token 2, and NT72 must generate the rest of the string, beginning with token 3 (t26).

NT72 has three binary rules:

a) NT72 → NT49 NT78  
b) NT72 → NT62 NT77  
c) NT72 → NT12 NT29

Token 3 is t26, and the ONLY lexical rule in the grammar that produces t26 is NT12 → 't26'.  
Therefore rule (c) must be used and NT29 must produce all tokens from position 4 onward.

NT29 itself has exactly one rule:

NT29 → NT40 NT16

So token 4 must be the first token generated by some derivation of NT40.  
Token 4 is t69.

We now inspect all possibilities for NT40 to start with t69:

• NT40 → 't3' / 't130' – starts with t3 or t130, not t69.  
• NT40 → NT51 NT74  – first token would be produced by NT51; NT51 can begin only with t71 or t7, never t69.  
• NT40 → NT60 NT58  – here the first token comes from NT28 because NT60 → NT28 NT4 and NT28 → 't69' | 't127' | 't105'.  
  So t69 can come from NT28, but then NT4 must account for the next token(s).  
  NT4 is either lexical 't30' (forcing the next token to be t30, which is actually t58 in the string)  
  or NT4 → NT30 NT71, which would make the next two tokens (positions 5 and 6) come from  
  NT30 (lexical 't58' or 't66') and NT71 (lexical 't22' or 't69'), respectively.  
  In the actual string positions 5 and 6 are t58 and t66 – the second of these (t66) cannot be produced by NT71, so this alternative also fails.

Hence no derivation of NT40 can start with t69 followed by the given continuation of the string, which means NT29 cannot generate the substring from token 4 onward.  
Consequently NT72 cannot generate the substring from token 3 onward, NT7 cannot generate tokens 2–36, and the start symbol S cannot generate the entire string.

Therefore the string is not in the language defined by the grammar.

No

The only production that can yield a first-token t36 is  

S → NT84 NT7 with NT84 → 't36'  

So the derivation must begin  

S ⇒ NT84 NT7 ⇒ 't36' NT7  

NT7 has three alternatives  

1. NT7 → 't125'  
2. NT7 → 't102'  
3. NT7 → NT40 NT72  

Because the second token of the string is t130, NT7 cannot take alternatives 1 or 2 (they would finish the derivation after a single additional token).  
Therefore NT7 must use alternative 3, giving

… ⇒ 't36' NT40 NT72

and the second token has to be generated by NT40.

The only rule capable of producing the single terminal t130 is the lexical rule  

NT40 → 't130'

Using any other rule for NT40 would make the first symbol produced by NT40 something other than t130, contradicting the string. Hence

… ⇒ 't36' 't130' NT72  

and the remaining 38 tokens must be generated by NT72 alone.

NT72 has four possibilities:

• NT72 → 't62' (1 token)  
• NT72 → NT12 NT29 (≥3 tokens, first token must come from NT12)  
• NT72 → NT62 NT77 (≥3 tokens, first token must come from NT62)  
• NT72 → NT49 NT78 (≥2 tokens, first token must come from NT49)

The first remaining token is t86.  
– NT12 can yield only t119, t31 or t26 (or strings beginning with those),  
– NT62 can yield only t117, t49, t37, t115, t129, t54, t56 or t32 (or strings beginning with those),  
so the rules NT72 → NT12 NT29 and NT72 → NT62 NT77 are impossible: neither NT12 nor NT62 can start with t86.  

The rule NT72 → 't62' is also impossible because 38 tokens remain.  

Thus the only chance is  

NT72 → NT49 NT78 with NT49 producing the first 37 of the remaining tokens and NT78 the last one.

But NT78 can only be  
 NT78 → 't101' or NT78 → 't39' or NT78 → NT65 NT64 (which must start with t105).  
Since the last token of the whole string is t39, NT78 would have to be 't39', leaving 37 tokens for NT49.

The first symbol of every derivation of NT49 must be produced by one of the following immediate alternatives:

• NT49 → 't108' (starts with t108)  
• NT49 → NT18 … (starts with t86 or t76)  
• NT49 → NT58 … (starts with t79 or t112)  
• NT49 → NT57 … (starts with t117, t49 or t37)  
• NT49 → NT16 … (whose first token must come from NT48 and can only be t117, t89 or t83)  

Hence the only alternative that can begin with t86 is NT49 → NT18 NT29 with NT18 → 't86'.  
This consumes just the single token t86, leaving 36 tokens that have to be generated by NT29.  
But NT29 has exactly one production:

NT29 → NT40 NT16

NT40, as already noted, can begin only with t130 (single-token rule) or with t3, t69, t127, t105, t71, etc. — never with t105 followed immediately by the sequence t58 t58 … that actually occurs next.  In particular:

• If NT40 uses its one–token rule, it would produce only a single terminal (t130 or t3).  
 The next token in the string is t105, so this fails.  

• If NT40 uses NT40 → NT60 NT58 or NT40 → NT51 NT74, its very first token must be t69, t127, t105, t71, or something produced by NT17 – none of which is followed by the pair t58 t58 that actually occurs.  Careful case-by-case inspection of all those possibilities shows that the second and third tokens produced by NT40 can never both be t58, so NT40 cannot match the substring t105 t58 t58… that must follow.

Consequently NT29 cannot generate the substring beginning with t105, hence NT49 cannot generate the required 37-token sequence, and so NT72 cannot generate the 38 tokens that remain after 't36 t130'.

Because every possible derivation for S is blocked, the grammar cannot produce the given string.

No

The first symbol of every sentence generated by the grammar must come from one of the three lefthand non-terminals that appear on the right of the start productions

S → NT61 NT57  
S → NT37 NT47  
S → NT84 NT7.

• NT61 can only yield the single terminals t96, t94, t93, t89, t18 or the pair t70 t72.  
• NT37 can only yield t50, t106, t114 or t21.  
• The only way to obtain the first word t121 is through the third alternative:
  NT84 → NT14 NT45 with NT14 → t121.

Hence any derivation of the string must begin

S ⇒ NT84 NT7 ⇒ NT14 NT45 NT7 ⇒ t121 … .

After emitting t121, NT45 has to cover the second word t109.  
NT45 may be

 – a single terminal (NT45 → t109), or  
 – the pair NT57 NT83 (which would force the second word to be t49, t117 or t37 – none of them is t109).

Therefore NT45 must be the one-word production NT45 → t109 and NT84 produces exactly the two-word prefix t121 t109.  
The rest of the input (the remaining 44 tokens, beginning with t127) has to be generated by NT7.

NT7 can only be

 NT7 → t125  (one word)  
 NT7 → t102  (one word)  
 NT7 → NT40 NT72.

So it must use the binary production NT7 → NT40 NT72, and NT40 has to start with the third word t127.

The only way for NT40 to generate a word that starts with t127 is through

NT40 → NT60 NT58  
  NT60 → NT28 NT4  with NT28 → t127.

Thus the first four words produced by NT40 would have to follow the scheme

t127  (from NT28)  
x     (from NT30)  
y     (from NT71)  
z     (from NT58, which can only be t79 or t112).

That forces the third, fourth and fifth words to be
 x ∈ {t66, t58}, y ∈ {t22, t69}, z ∈ {t79, t112}.

In the given string the third, fourth and fifth words are

t127 t66 t66 …

—the fifth word is t66, which is impossible (it must be t22 or t69).  
Hence NT40 cannot produce a prefix beginning with t127, so NT7 cannot begin with t127, contradicting the required continuation of the sentence.

Since no start-production alternative can match the initial token sequence of the string, the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No
